        <h2>Presence in the Process</h2>

        <blockquote>Presence in the process leads to aligned action.</blockquote>

        <p>Wrestlers are guided to focus internally—on the sensations, alignment, and organization of their own body—rather than on external outcomes or performance metrics.</p>

        <p>By cultivating an internal perspective, the nervous system settles and the body responds more clearly to the unfolding moment.</p>

        <p>This is why our wrestlers practice their 5-step process each morning. The purpose is not simply completion, but to develop presence and integrity with the process itself.</p>

        <h3>Full Body Awareness</h3>

        <p>Full body awareness deepens internal connection and enhances integration.</p>

        <p>When awareness is distributed throughout the entire body, wrestlers can sense balance, structure, and center while remaining connected to their opponent and environment.</p>

        <p>This embodies the core principles of internal martial arts, where movement is guided from awareness and alignment rather than muscular effort alone.</p>

        <h3>River Coherence</h3>

        <p>We use the phrase:</p>

        <blockquote>“Surrendering to the current of the river.”</blockquote>

        <p>This represents River Coherence—a state where the body and nervous system are organized, responsive, and flowing.</p>

        <p>Full body awareness is not required to experience River Coherence, but it significantly amplifies it, allowing the system to move as one integrated unit.</p>

        <p>By practicing the internal martial arts principles within the 5-step process, wrestlers strengthen their embodied awareness, and the flow of movement emerges naturally from presence.</p>

        <p>Over time, wrestling becomes more than technique execution—it becomes aligned action emerging from internal presence.</p>

